###Set Up SSH Key Authentication on a Linux Server

##Purpose:
This document outlines the standard procedure for configuring SSH key authentication on a linux server. For this document, 
we will be using Red Hat Enterprise Linux as the server, and Windows 11 aas the workstation.

##Audience:
This document is intended for system admins, server admins, and other member of the IT team that are involved in configuring 
communication with the server.

##Scope:
This document covers the following:
- Preparing a Linux server for remote administration
- Installing SSH
- Configuring SSH, key-based access, basic firewall SSH access, and basic SSH security practices
- Generating and transfering keys
- Verifying SSH services

##Definition:
RHEL:          Red Hat Enterprise Linux
SSH:           Secure Shell | A protocol used to remotely access servers and workstations
SSH Key:       A cryptographic file that can be transfered to another device for SSH authentication
Terminal:      RHEL program that allows users to type commands
Command Line:  Windows program that allows users to type commands
Firewall:      A program that protects a device by following a set of rules

