##Execution Steps:
(Note: There are screenshots in the "Screenshots" folder on the Github page if needed)
#Step 1: Aquire Prerequisites and Clearance:
Step 1.1: Identify Server:
- Find the server that you want to configure SSH key authentication on.
Step 1.2: Get clearance/login credentials:
- Ask the administrator with clearance if you are allowed to configure SSH key authentication on.
- Get a login that is used on the server that has priveleges to configure SSH on the server.
Step 1.3: Get any peripheral devices needed to interface with the server:
- You will need a method of interfacing with the server. Options include:
  - Monitor, mouse, and keyboard
  - Console cable, and laptop
  - Rack mounted monitor and keyboard
- The interface method is up to you, but we will be simulating a physical connection with a monitor, mouse, 
and keyboard using VMWare Workstation.
Step 1.4: Identify client device:
- SSH connections has a client connecting to a recipient. The server is the recipient, but we need a client to send the connetion. 
- The client should be a workstation/laptop that can comnnect to the server. We will be using a Windows 11 laptop.

#Step 2: Set Up Enviroment:
Step 2.1: Connect server with power and all peripherals needed:
- Make sure the server has a source of power.
- Connect any peripherals chosen in Step 1.3.
Step 2.2: Turn on server and log in:
- Turn on the server and let it boot to the RHEL login screen.
- Log in using the credentials aquired in step 1.2.
Step 2.3: Get to the terminal:
- Once logged in, click the search bar at the top center of the screen.
  - If you don't see the search bar, press the red hat icon at the top left of the screen to reveal it.
- Type "terminal", and press enter.
Step 2.4: Connect client to server:
- Connect the client device decided in Step 1.4 to the server.
- Verify that the connection is open by:
  - Checking the lights on the ethernet ports on the client and server to see if their on
  - Search "View network connections" in the windows searchbar and check the properties of the connection 
  used to see if its operational

#Step 3: Verifying/Downloading SSH Services:
Step 3.1: Verify SSH:
- In the terminal, type "systemctl status sshd.service", and press enter. The output should show you if SSH services are 
already running on the server.
  - If the output contains the green text "active (running)", that means that SSH services are currently functional, 
  and you can skip to Step 4.
  - If the output doesn't contain the green text, we will have to download the SSH services. This document will show how to do that 
  in the following steps.
Step 3.2: Download SSH:
- Type "yum install openssh-server" into the terminal to download the most recent SSH services
- Type "systemctl start sshd" to start the SSH services.

#Step 4: Create SSH Key On Client Device:
Step 4.1: Open command line in client
- Open a command line window on the client device. You can do this by typing "cmd" in the windows searchbar, and pressing enter
Step 4.2: Create the SSH key 
- In the command line, type the following commands:
  - "ssh-keygen -t rsa"
  - *Insert file location you want to save the SSH key*
  - *Insert password to use the SSH key, or leave empty for no password. A password is highly reccomended for security*
  - *Repeat input from the previouse line*
Step 4.3: Verify SSH key
- On the client command line, go to the file location of the public file. This can be done using the cd command
  - Example "cd C:\Users\'Insert Username'/.ssh"
- Type "dir", and press enter. The output should include the public key (Example: "id_rsa.pub")

#Step 5: Transfer Public SSH Key To Server:
Step 5.1: Verify that server has the .ssh directory:
- The .ssh directory is where the public key from the client will be stored. On the terminal on the server, type "cd ~" 
to verify that you are in the right directory
- Type "ls -la", then press enter. If the output includes ".ssh", then you already have the file. If you already have 
the correct file, move to Step 5.3.
Step 5.2: Create the .ssh directory:
- In the terminal, type "mkdir .ssh" then press enter. This will create the directory.
- Use the "ls -la" to verify that the .ssh directory was created.
Step 5.3: Transfer the public SSH key
- Back to the client command line. Type the following commands:
  - "scp 'public key name' 'Server Admin User'@'server ip address':~/.ssh/authorized_keys"
    -  Example "scp id_rsa.pub admin@172.19.214.249:~/.ssh/authorized_keys"
  - "yes"
  - *Insert Password if applicable*
Step 5.4: Verify transfer:
- On the server terminal, enter the following commands:
  - "cd ~/.ssh/"
  - "ls"
- The output should list "authorized_keys" as an item.

#Step 6: Edit SSH_Config File On Server:
Step 6.1: Edit sshd_config file in Nano
- In the server terminal enter the command "sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config" to edit the ssh configuration file.
  - May need to enter the root user password.
- In the sshd_config file, edit the following line in the document to the new lines:
  - "#PasswordAuthentication yes" --> "PasswordAuthentication no"
- Verify that the "AuthorizedKeysFile" is set to ".ssh/autheroized_keys"
- Once all edits are made, press "X", then press "Y" to save modifications.
- Lastly, press enter to save to the "sshd_config" file
Step 6.2: Restart SSH services:
- In the server terminal, enter "systemctl restart sshd.service"
  - You may need to enter the admin password

#Step 7: Modify/Verify Firewall:
Step 7.1: Add an SSH firewall rule:
- In the server terminal, enter this command "sudo firewall-cmd --zone=public --permanent --add-service=ssh"
  - If the output says "Warning: ALREADY_ENABLED: ssh; success", then the rule is already in place, and you can skip to Step 8.
- Enter this command "sudo firewall-cmd --reload" to apply the modification

#Step 8: Connect Client To Server:
Step 8.1: 
- On the client command line, enter the command "ssh -i id_rsa 'Insert server account'@'Insert server IP address"
  - You will need to enter the SSH key password if you made one.

#Common Issues/Troubleshooting:
Issue 1: SSH communication is blocked
- Can the client ping the server? If not:
  - Check both devices connection properties. (Windows: Network Connection Settings | RHEL: "ip a" command)
    - Check ports ipv4 settings on windows (Windows: Right click port/Properties/(TCP/IPv4))
    - Check edit port settings on RHEL (RHEL: nmcli con up 'insert connection' | nmcli con modify 'insert connection' ...)
      - To learn more on how to modify RHEL connections, use the "man nmcli" command
- If the devices can ping eachother, something might be blocking the SSH services.
  - Revisit Step 7 to verify that you configured the firewall correctly.
Issue 2: Server can't download SSH:
- Check if the server is registered with this command "sudo subscription-manager identity"
  - If the output says that "This system is not yet registered...", then you will have to get the server registered.
    - RHEL registration is beyond this document, but you can find documentaion on this process at Red Hat Documentation.

